problem.markdown:
>>When referring to group fairness, which of the following option is false? <<

( ) Group fairness can be defined as an equal probability of being assigned to the positive predicted class. {{This is in fact true. An example of a group fairness equation is [mathjaxinline] p(d=1|G=f) = p(d=1|G=m)[/mathjaxinline] which means “the probability of a positive predicted class being predicted given that the protected attribute is female (gender = female) is equal to the positive predicted class being predicted given that the protected attribute is male (gender = male)”.}}
( ) Group fairness is also known as statistical (demographic) parity, equal acceptance rate and benchmarking. {{This is in fact true. All of these aliases are valid terms for group fairness. }}
(x) Group fairness in the context of fairness through awareness states that similar individuals should have similar classification. {{This statement is not true. This is, in fact, the definition of individual fairness. Group fairness is defined as an equal probability of being assigned to the positive predicted class.}}
( ) In order to satisfy group fairness, the model may select qualified applicants in one group, but unqualified applications in another group. {{This is in fact true. The group fairness notion permits that a classifier selects qualified applicants in a female group for example, but unqualified individuals in a male group. }}
